00:00:21.780 --> 00:00:25.020
PROFESSOR: Today we're going
to keep on going

00:00:25.020 --> 00:00:30.660
with related rates.

00:00:30.660 --> 00:00:35.600
And you may recall that last
time we were in the middle of

00:00:35.600 --> 00:00:39.000
a problem with this geometry.

00:00:39.000 --> 00:00:41.260
There was a right triangle.

00:00:41.260 --> 00:00:43.190
There was a road.

00:00:43.190 --> 00:00:47.000
Which was going this way,
from right to left.

00:00:47.000 --> 00:00:53.830
And the police were up here,
monitoring the situation.

00:00:53.830 --> 00:00:55.990
30 feet from the road.

00:00:55.990 --> 00:00:59.990
And you're here.

00:00:59.990 --> 00:01:04.370
And you're heading this way.

00:01:04.370 --> 00:01:06.525
Maybe it's a two lane highway,
but anyway it's only going

00:01:06.525 --> 00:01:07.680
this direction.

00:01:07.680 --> 00:01:11.670
And this distance was 50 feet.

00:01:11.670 --> 00:01:17.320
So, because you're moving, this
distance is varying and

00:01:17.320 --> 00:01:19.120
so we gave it a letter.

00:01:19.120 --> 00:01:21.900
And, similarly, your distance
to the foot of the

00:01:21.900 --> 00:01:25.050
perpendicular with the
road is also varying.

00:01:25.050 --> 00:01:29.890
At this instant it's 40, because
this is a 3, 4, 5

00:01:29.890 --> 00:01:31.570
right triangle.

00:01:31.570 --> 00:01:35.830
So this was the situation that
we were in last time.

00:01:35.830 --> 00:01:38.090
And we're going to pick
up where we left off.

00:01:38.090 --> 00:01:50.860
The question is, are you
speeding if the rate of change

00:01:50.860 --> 00:01:56.510
of D with respect to t is
80 feet per second.

00:01:56.510 --> 00:02:00.680
Now, technically that would be
- 80, because you're going

00:02:00.680 --> 00:02:03.030
towards the policemen.

00:02:03.030 --> 00:02:05.530
Alright, so D is shrinking
at a rate of

00:02:05.530 --> 00:02:10.550
- 80 feet per second.

00:02:10.550 --> 00:02:16.910
And I remind you that 95 feet
per second is approximately

00:02:16.910 --> 00:02:17.660
the speed limit.

00:02:17.660 --> 00:02:21.370
Which is 65 miles per hour.

00:02:21.370 --> 00:02:24.850
So, again, this is where
we were last time.

00:02:24.850 --> 00:02:30.150
And, got a little question
mark there.

00:02:30.150 --> 00:02:34.140
And so let's solve
this problem.

00:02:34.140 --> 00:02:37.480
So, this is the setup.

00:02:37.480 --> 00:02:38.880
There's a right triangle.

00:02:38.880 --> 00:02:42.290
So there's a relationship
between these lengths.

00:02:42.290 --> 00:02:49.800
And the relationship is that
x ^2 + 30 ^2 = D ^2.

00:02:49.800 --> 00:02:54.020
So that's the first relationship
that we have. And

00:02:54.020 --> 00:02:55.700
the second relationship
that we have, we've

00:02:55.700 --> 00:02:57.380
already written down.

00:02:57.380 --> 00:03:08.620
Which is dx / dt - oops, sorry.
dD / dt = minus 80.

00:03:08.620 --> 00:03:14.920
Now, the idea here is relatively
straightforward.

00:03:14.920 --> 00:03:17.790
We just want to use
differentiation.

00:03:17.790 --> 00:03:25.810
Now, you could solve for x.

00:03:25.810 --> 00:03:31.580
Alright, x is the square root
of D^2 - 30 squared.

00:03:31.580 --> 00:03:32.820
That's one possibility.

00:03:32.820 --> 00:03:36.060
But this is basically
a waste of time.

00:03:36.060 --> 00:03:37.810
It's a waste of your time.

00:03:37.810 --> 00:03:45.550
So it's easier, or easiest, to
follow this method of implicit

00:03:45.550 --> 00:03:47.380
differentiation, which
I want to encourage

00:03:47.380 --> 00:03:49.080
you to get used to.

00:03:49.080 --> 00:03:51.490
Namely, we just differentiate
this equation

00:03:51.490 --> 00:03:53.460
with respect to time.

00:03:53.460 --> 00:03:56.050
Now, when you do that, you have
to remember that you are

00:03:56.050 --> 00:03:59.120
not allowed to plug
in a constant.

00:03:59.120 --> 00:04:01.110
Namely 40, for t.

00:04:01.110 --> 00:04:03.070
You have to keep in mind what's
really going on in this

00:04:03.070 --> 00:04:05.670
problem which is that x is
moving, it's changing.

00:04:05.670 --> 00:04:07.250
And D is also changing.

00:04:07.250 --> 00:04:10.380
So you have to differentiate
first before

00:04:10.380 --> 00:04:12.030
you plug in the values.

00:04:12.030 --> 00:04:15.610
So the easiest thing is to use,
in this case, implicit

00:04:15.610 --> 00:04:20.130
differentiation.

00:04:20.130 --> 00:04:33.000
And if I do that, I get 2x dx /
dt is equal to 2D (dD / dt).

00:04:33.000 --> 00:04:34.910
No more DDT left.

00:04:34.910 --> 00:04:36.640
We hope.

00:04:36.640 --> 00:04:39.160
Except in this blackboard.

00:04:39.160 --> 00:04:40.690
So there's our situation.

00:04:40.690 --> 00:04:48.070
Now, if I just plug in,
now I can plug in.

00:04:48.070 --> 00:04:52.820
In values. so this is after
taking the derivative.

00:04:52.820 --> 00:04:55.750
And, indeed, we have here 2
times the value for x which is

00:04:55.750 --> 00:04:57.500
40 at this instant.

00:04:57.500 --> 00:05:01.070
And then we have dx / dt.

00:05:01.070 --> 00:05:07.510
And that's equal to 2
(D), which is 50.

00:05:07.510 --> 00:05:12.900
And then dD / dt is - 80.

00:05:12.900 --> 00:05:19.180
So the 80's cancel and we
see that dv / dt = -

00:05:19.180 --> 00:05:21.660
100 feet per second.

00:05:21.660 --> 00:05:27.340
And so the answer to the
question is yes.

00:05:27.340 --> 00:05:30.770
Although you probably wouldn't
be pulled over for this much

00:05:30.770 --> 00:05:32.540
of a violation.

00:05:32.540 --> 00:05:36.470
So that's, right, it's more than
65 miles an hour, by a

00:05:36.470 --> 00:05:41.190
little bit.

00:05:41.190 --> 00:05:43.380
So that's the end of
this question.

00:05:43.380 --> 00:05:46.460
And usually in these rate of
change or related rates

00:05:46.460 --> 00:05:48.530
questions, this is considered
to be the answer to the

00:05:48.530 --> 00:05:53.530
question, if you like.

00:05:53.530 --> 00:05:55.600
So that's one example.

00:05:55.600 --> 00:05:58.960
I'm going to give one more
example before we go on to

00:05:58.960 --> 00:06:04.560
some other applications implicit
differentiation.

00:06:04.560 --> 00:06:11.520
So my second example is going
to be, you have a it is a

00:06:11.520 --> 00:06:17.250
conical tank.

00:06:17.250 --> 00:06:26.640
With top of radius 4
feet, let's say.

00:06:26.640 --> 00:06:31.770
And depth 10 feet.

00:06:31.770 --> 00:06:34.710
So that's our situation.

00:06:34.710 --> 00:06:37.730
And then it's being
filled with water.

00:06:37.730 --> 00:06:42.830
So, is being filled
with water.

00:06:42.830 --> 00:06:49.900
At 2 cubic feet per minute.

00:06:49.900 --> 00:06:52.980
So there is our situation.

00:06:52.980 --> 00:07:07.580
And then the question is, how
fast is the water rising when

00:07:07.580 --> 00:07:15.040
it is at depth 5 feet?

00:07:15.040 --> 00:07:19.670
So if this thing is half-full
in the sense, well not

00:07:19.670 --> 00:07:21.770
half-full in terms
of total volume.

00:07:21.770 --> 00:07:29.160
But half-full in terms of
height, what's the speed at

00:07:29.160 --> 00:07:36.540
which the water is rising.

00:07:36.540 --> 00:07:39.970
So, how do we set up
problems like this?

00:07:39.970 --> 00:07:42.240
Well, we talked about
this last time.

00:07:42.240 --> 00:07:51.780
The first step is to set up
a diagram and variables.

00:07:51.780 --> 00:07:54.450
And I'm just going to
draw the picture.

00:07:54.450 --> 00:07:58.320
And I'm actually going to
draw the picture twice.

00:07:58.320 --> 00:08:01.590
So here's the conical tank.

00:08:01.590 --> 00:08:05.040
And we have this radius,
which is 4.

00:08:05.040 --> 00:08:07.970
And we have this height,
which is 10.

00:08:07.970 --> 00:08:10.950
So that's just to allow me to
think about this problem.

00:08:10.950 --> 00:08:18.730
Now, it turns out because we
have a varying depth and so

00:08:18.730 --> 00:08:21.730
on, and this is just the top.

00:08:21.730 --> 00:08:24.530
That I'd better depict also the
level at which the water

00:08:24.530 --> 00:08:26.700
actually is at present.

00:08:26.700 --> 00:08:30.890
And furthermore, it's better to
do this schematically, as

00:08:30.890 --> 00:08:31.830
you'll see.

00:08:31.830 --> 00:08:38.200
So the key point here is to
draw this triangle here.

00:08:38.200 --> 00:08:45.230
Which shows me the 10 and shows
me the 4, over here.

00:08:45.230 --> 00:08:48.290
And then imagine that I'm
filling it partway.

00:08:48.290 --> 00:08:50.550
So maybe we'll put that
water level in in

00:08:50.550 --> 00:08:52.400
another color here.

00:08:52.400 --> 00:08:54.370
So here's the water level.

00:08:54.370 --> 00:08:57.840
And the water level, I'm going
to depict that horizontal

00:08:57.840 --> 00:08:59.770
distance here, as r.

00:08:59.770 --> 00:09:00.950
That's going to be
my variable.

00:09:00.950 --> 00:09:04.150
That's the radius of the
top of the water.

00:09:04.150 --> 00:09:06.980
So I'm taking a cross-section
of this, because that

00:09:06.980 --> 00:09:10.230
geometrically the only thing
I have to keep track of.

00:09:10.230 --> 00:09:11.820
At least initially.

00:09:11.820 --> 00:09:14.630
So this is our water level.

00:09:14.630 --> 00:09:18.540
And it's really rotated
around.

00:09:18.540 --> 00:09:23.130
But I'm depicting just this one
half-slice of the picture.

00:09:23.130 --> 00:09:26.300
And then similarly,
I have the height.

00:09:26.300 --> 00:09:30.390
Which is this dimension there.

00:09:30.390 --> 00:09:32.570
Or, if you like, the
depth of the water.

00:09:32.570 --> 00:09:42.140
So the water has filled us up,
up to this point here.

00:09:42.140 --> 00:09:46.850
So I set it up this way so that
it's clear that we have

00:09:46.850 --> 00:09:47.450
two triangles here.

00:09:47.450 --> 00:09:50.210
And that one piece of
information we can get from

00:09:50.210 --> 00:09:53.880
the geometry is the similar
triangles information.

00:09:53.880 --> 00:09:59.870
Namely, that r / h = 4 / 10.

00:09:59.870 --> 00:10:09.950
So this is by far the most
typical geometric fact that

00:10:09.950 --> 00:10:13.450
you'll have to glean
from a picture.

00:10:13.450 --> 00:10:17.280
So that's one piece of
information that we get from

00:10:17.280 --> 00:10:18.920
this picture.

00:10:18.920 --> 00:10:23.250
Now, the second thing we have
to do is set up formulas for

00:10:23.250 --> 00:10:26.470
the volume of water,
and then figure out

00:10:26.470 --> 00:10:27.330
what's going on here.

00:10:27.330 --> 00:10:33.460
So the volume of water
is, of a cone.

00:10:33.460 --> 00:10:37.360
So again, you have to know
something about geometry to do

00:10:37.360 --> 00:10:40.290
many of these problems. So you
have to know that the volume

00:10:40.290 --> 00:10:44.500
of a cone is 1/3 base
times height.

00:10:44.500 --> 00:10:45.900
Now, this one is upside down.

00:10:45.900 --> 00:10:50.020
The base is on the top and it's
going down but it works

00:10:50.020 --> 00:10:50.720
the same way.

00:10:50.720 --> 00:10:52.270
That doesn't affect volume.

00:10:52.270 --> 00:10:57.450
So it's 1/3 and the base is
pi r^2, that's the base.

00:10:57.450 --> 00:11:01.890
And times h, which
is the height.

00:11:01.890 --> 00:11:06.290
So this is the setup
for this problem.

00:11:06.290 --> 00:11:12.270
And now, having our
relationship, we have one

00:11:12.270 --> 00:11:14.580
relationship left that
we have to remember.

00:11:14.580 --> 00:11:15.920
Because we have one
more piece of

00:11:15.920 --> 00:11:17.630
information in this problem.

00:11:17.630 --> 00:11:20.990
Namely, how fast the
volume is changing.

00:11:20.990 --> 00:11:22.960
It's going at 2 cubic
feet per minute.

00:11:22.960 --> 00:11:29.740
It's increasing, so that
means that dv / dt = 2.

00:11:29.740 --> 00:11:35.340
So I've now gotten rid of all
the words and I have only

00:11:35.340 --> 00:11:38.010
formulas left.

00:11:38.010 --> 00:11:43.960
I started here with the words,
I drew some pictures, and I

00:11:43.960 --> 00:11:44.740
derived some formulas.

00:11:44.740 --> 00:11:46.200
Actually, there's one
thing missing.

00:11:46.200 --> 00:11:49.930
What's missing?

00:11:49.930 --> 00:11:52.570
Yeah.

00:11:52.570 --> 00:11:57.230
STUDENT: [INAUDIBLE]

00:11:57.230 --> 00:11:57.740
PROFESSOR: Exactly.

00:11:57.740 --> 00:11:58.420
What you want to find.

00:11:58.420 --> 00:12:00.690
What I left out is
the question.

00:12:00.690 --> 00:12:15.110
So the question is, what
is dh / dt when h = 5?

00:12:15.110 --> 00:12:20.600
So that's the question here.

00:12:20.600 --> 00:12:22.630
Now, we've got the whole problem
and we never have to

00:12:22.630 --> 00:12:25.510
look at it again if you like.

00:12:25.510 --> 00:12:32.610
We just have to pay attention
to this piece here.

00:12:32.610 --> 00:12:34.780
So let's carry it out.

00:12:34.780 --> 00:12:36.870
So what happens here.

00:12:36.870 --> 00:12:39.190
So look, you could do this by
implicit differentiation.

00:12:39.190 --> 00:12:43.180
But it's so easy to express r
as a function of h that that

00:12:43.180 --> 00:12:44.560
seems kind of foolish.

00:12:44.560 --> 00:12:48.900
So let's write r as 2/5 h.

00:12:48.900 --> 00:12:51.280
That's coming from this
first equation here.

00:12:51.280 --> 00:12:53.800
And then let's substitute
that in.

00:12:53.800 --> 00:13:04.810
That means that v = 1/3
pi ( 2/5 h^2) h.

00:13:04.810 --> 00:13:06.630
And now I have to differentiate
that.

00:13:06.630 --> 00:13:08.850
So now I will use implicit
differentiation.

00:13:08.850 --> 00:13:12.200
It's very foolish at this point
to take cube roots to

00:13:12.200 --> 00:13:13.320
solve for h.

00:13:13.320 --> 00:13:16.080
You just get yourself into
a bunch of junk.

00:13:16.080 --> 00:13:18.580
So there is a stage at which
we're still using implicit

00:13:18.580 --> 00:13:19.490
differentiation here.

00:13:19.490 --> 00:13:24.780
I'm not going to try to solve
for h as a function of v.

00:13:24.780 --> 00:13:26.700
Instead I'm just differentiating
straight out

00:13:26.700 --> 00:13:28.620
from this formula, which
is relatively easy to

00:13:28.620 --> 00:13:29.530
differentiate.

00:13:29.530 --> 00:13:36.210
So this is dv / dt, which
of course = 2 and if I

00:13:36.210 --> 00:13:39.640
differentiate it I just get this
constant, pi / 3, this

00:13:39.640 --> 00:13:42.390
other constant, (2/5)^2.

00:13:42.390 --> 00:13:45.200
And then I have to differentiate
h^3.

00:13:45.200 --> 00:13:47.290
(h^2)h.

00:13:47.290 --> 00:13:53.140
So that's 3h^2 ( dh / dt).

00:13:53.140 --> 00:13:59.760
That's the chain rule.

00:13:59.760 --> 00:14:02.080
So now let's plug in
all of our numbers.

00:14:02.080 --> 00:14:07.110
Again, the other theme is, you
don't plug in numbers, fixed

00:14:07.110 --> 00:14:09.600
numbers, until everything
has stopped moving.

00:14:09.600 --> 00:14:11.640
At this point, we've
already calculated

00:14:11.640 --> 00:14:12.790
our rates of change.

00:14:12.790 --> 00:14:14.140
So now I can put
in the numbers.

00:14:14.140 --> 00:14:26.010
So, 2 = pi 3 ( 2/5)^2( 3), and
then h was 5, so this is 5^2.

00:14:26.010 --> 00:14:27.870
And then I have dh / dt.

00:14:27.870 --> 00:14:31.600
There's only one unknown thing
left in this problem,

00:14:31.600 --> 00:14:32.560
which is dh / dt.

00:14:32.560 --> 00:14:33.990
Everything else is a number.

00:14:33.990 --> 00:14:36.800
And if you do all the
cancellations, you see that

00:14:36.800 --> 00:14:38.210
this cancels this.

00:14:38.210 --> 00:14:41.280
One of the 2's cancels - well,
this cancels this.

00:14:41.280 --> 00:14:42.690
And then one of the
2's cancels that.

00:14:42.690 --> 00:14:54.080
So all-told what we have here
is that dh / dt = 1 / 2 pi.

00:14:54.080 --> 00:14:58.700
And so that happens to
be feet per second.

00:14:58.700 --> 00:15:04.610
This is the whole story.

00:15:04.610 --> 00:15:05.680
Questions, way back there.

00:15:05.680 --> 00:15:10.040
STUDENT: [INAUDIBLE]

00:15:10.040 --> 00:15:11.630
PROFESSOR: Where did I get --
the question is where did I

00:15:11.630 --> 00:15:14.590
get r = 2/5 h from.

00:15:14.590 --> 00:15:17.680
The answer was, it came from
similar triangles,

00:15:17.680 --> 00:15:19.020
which is over here.

00:15:19.020 --> 00:15:20.380
I did this similar
triangle thing.

00:15:20.380 --> 00:15:26.280
And I got this relationship
here. r / h = 4/10, but then I

00:15:26.280 --> 00:15:31.790
canceled it, got 2/5 and
brought the h over.

00:15:31.790 --> 00:15:32.890
Another question, over here.

00:15:32.890 --> 00:15:45.470
STUDENT: [INAUDIBLE]

00:15:45.470 --> 00:15:53.100
PROFESSOR: The question
was the following.

00:15:53.100 --> 00:15:56.020
Suppose you're at this
stage, can you write

00:15:56.020 --> 00:15:58.310
from here dv / dh.

00:15:58.310 --> 00:15:59.560
So, suppose you're here.

00:15:59.560 --> 00:16:01.390
And work out what this is.

00:16:01.390 --> 00:16:05.030
It's going to end up being
some constant times h^2.

00:16:05.030 --> 00:16:14.990
And then also use dv / dt
= dv / dh ( dh / dt).

00:16:14.990 --> 00:16:17.520
Which the chain rule.

00:16:17.520 --> 00:16:20.830
And the answer is yes.

00:16:20.830 --> 00:16:24.500
We can do that, and indeed
that is what my

00:16:24.500 --> 00:16:26.310
next sentence is.

00:16:26.310 --> 00:16:27.750
That's exactly what
I'm saying.

00:16:27.750 --> 00:16:30.240
So when I said this
- sorry, when you

00:16:30.240 --> 00:16:32.780
said this, I did that.

00:16:32.780 --> 00:16:34.080
That's exactly what I did.

00:16:34.080 --> 00:16:41.110
This chunk is exactly dv / dh.

00:16:41.110 --> 00:16:43.390
That's just what I'm doing.

00:16:43.390 --> 00:16:44.730
OK.

00:16:44.730 --> 00:16:48.750
So, definitely, that's
what I had in mind.

00:16:48.750 --> 00:16:49.760
Yeah, another question.

00:16:49.760 --> 00:16:55.280
STUDENT: [INAUDIBLE]

00:16:55.280 --> 00:16:56.730
PROFESSOR: You're asking
me whether my

00:16:56.730 --> 00:16:58.040
arithmetic is right or not?

00:16:58.040 --> 00:17:03.890
STUDENT: [INAUDIBLE]

00:17:03.890 --> 00:17:06.850
PROFESSOR: Pi - per second.

