00:21:54.000 --> 00:21:55.570
Like, a suspension bridge.

00:21:55.570 --> 00:21:58.130
This, among many problems.
It's a very serious and

00:21:58.130 --> 00:21:59.350
important problem.

00:21:59.350 --> 00:22:02.940
And this is the simplest
one of this type.

00:22:02.940 --> 00:22:04.990
So we've got our shape here.

00:22:04.990 --> 00:22:07.770
This should be a straight
line, maybe not quite as

00:22:07.770 --> 00:22:10.920
angled as that.

00:22:10.920 --> 00:22:13.520
The first, we've already drawn
the diagram and we've more or

00:22:13.520 --> 00:22:16.010
less visualized what's
going on here.

00:22:16.010 --> 00:22:21.460
But the first step after the
diagram is to give letters.

00:22:21.460 --> 00:22:24.630
Is to label things
appropriately.

00:22:24.630 --> 00:22:27.270
And I do not expect you
to be able to do

00:22:27.270 --> 00:22:29.170
this, at this stage.

00:22:29.170 --> 00:22:31.390
Because it requires a
lot of experience.

00:22:31.390 --> 00:22:33.040
But I'm going to
do it for you.

00:22:33.040 --> 00:22:34.630
We're going to just do that.

00:22:34.630 --> 00:22:37.390
So the simplest thing
to do is to use the

00:22:37.390 --> 00:22:39.800
coordinates of the plane.

00:22:39.800 --> 00:22:43.750
And if you do that, it's also
easiest to use the origin.

00:22:43.750 --> 00:22:46.590
My favorite number is 0 and
it should be yours, too.

00:22:46.590 --> 00:22:51.420
So we're going to make
this point be (0, 0).

00:22:51.420 --> 00:22:54.550
Now, there's another fixed
point in this problem.

00:22:54.550 --> 00:22:57.200
And it's this point over here.

00:22:57.200 --> 00:22:58.880
And we don't know what
its coordinates are.

00:22:58.880 --> 00:23:00.850
So we're just going to give
them letters, a and b.

00:23:00.850 --> 00:23:02.790
But those letters are
going to be fixed

00:23:02.790 --> 00:23:06.110
numbers in this problem.

00:23:06.110 --> 00:23:08.840
And we want to solve it for
all possible a's and b's.

00:23:08.840 --> 00:23:11.400
Now, the interesting thing,
remember, is what happens when

00:23:11.400 --> 00:23:12.630
b Is not 0.

00:23:12.630 --> 00:23:16.250
If b = 0, we already have a clue
that the point should be

00:23:16.250 --> 00:23:16.950
the center point.

00:23:16.950 --> 00:23:19.440
It should be exactly that x,
the middle point, which I'm

00:23:19.440 --> 00:23:22.730
going to label in a second,
is halfway in between.

00:23:22.730 --> 00:23:25.930
So now the variable point that
I'm going to use is down here.

00:23:25.930 --> 00:23:30.220
I'm going to call this
point (x, y).

00:23:30.220 --> 00:23:31.600
So here's my setup.

00:23:31.600 --> 00:23:34.760
I've now given labels
to all the things on

00:23:34.760 --> 00:23:37.800
the diagram so far.

00:23:37.800 --> 00:23:42.260
Most of the things
on the diagram.

00:23:42.260 --> 00:23:47.700
So now, what else
do I have to do?

00:23:47.700 --> 00:23:54.930
Well, I have to explain
to you that this is a

00:23:54.930 --> 00:23:56.850
minimization problem.

00:23:56.850 --> 00:24:01.270
What happens, actually,
physically is that the weight

00:24:01.270 --> 00:24:03.050
settles to the lowest point.

00:24:03.050 --> 00:24:05.820
That's the thing that has the
lowest potential energy.

00:24:05.820 --> 00:24:09.370
So we're minimizing
a function.

00:24:09.370 --> 00:24:13.260
And it's this curve here.

00:24:13.260 --> 00:24:17.000
The constraint is that we're
restricted to this curve.

00:24:17.000 --> 00:24:18.660
So this is a constraint curve.

00:24:18.660 --> 00:24:24.590
And we want the lowest
point of this curve.

00:24:24.590 --> 00:24:29.160
So now, we need a little bit
more language in order to

00:24:29.160 --> 00:24:31.180
describe what it is
that we've got.

00:24:31.180 --> 00:24:36.500
And the constraint curve, we
got it in a particular way.

00:24:36.500 --> 00:24:39.320
Namely, we strung some string
from here to there.

00:24:39.320 --> 00:24:41.980
And what happens at all these
points is that the total

00:24:41.980 --> 00:24:45.920
length of the string
is the same.

00:24:45.920 --> 00:24:49.300
So one way of expressing the
constraint is that the length

00:24:49.300 --> 00:24:52.270
of the string is constant.

00:24:52.270 --> 00:24:54.690
And so in order to figure out
what the constraint is, what

00:24:54.690 --> 00:24:58.120
this curve is, I have to
describe that analytically.

00:24:58.120 --> 00:25:01.830
And I'm going to do that by
drawing in some helping lines.

00:25:01.830 --> 00:25:03.720
Namely, some right triangles
to figure out

00:25:03.720 --> 00:25:05.400
what this length is.

00:25:05.400 --> 00:25:07.290
And what the other length is.

00:25:07.290 --> 00:25:09.550
So this length is pretty
easy if I draw a

00:25:09.550 --> 00:25:11.410
right triangle here.

00:25:11.410 --> 00:25:14.410
Because we go over x
and we go down y.

00:25:14.410 --> 00:25:19.150
So this length is the square
root of x^2 + y^2.

00:25:19.150 --> 00:25:22.420
That's the Pythagorean
theorem.

00:25:22.420 --> 00:25:26.200
Similarly, over here, I'm going
to get another length.

00:25:26.200 --> 00:25:28.360
Which is a little
bit of a mess.

00:25:28.360 --> 00:25:30.670
It's the vertical.

00:25:30.670 --> 00:25:35.290
So I'm just going to label one
half of it, so that you see.

00:25:35.290 --> 00:25:38.600
So this horizontal
distance is x.

00:25:38.600 --> 00:25:41.810
And this horizontal distance
from this top point with this

00:25:41.810 --> 00:25:44.000
right angle, over there.

00:25:44.000 --> 00:25:47.660
It starts at x and ends at a.

00:25:47.660 --> 00:25:50.820
The right-most point is
a in the x coordinate.

00:25:50.820 --> 00:25:56.150
So the whole distance
is a - x.

00:25:56.150 --> 00:26:00.700
So that's this leg of
this right triangle.

00:26:00.700 --> 00:26:05.770
And, similarly, the vertical
distance will be b - y.

00:26:05.770 --> 00:26:08.300
And so, the formula here, which
is a little complicated

00:26:08.300 --> 00:26:17.160
for this length, is the square
root of (a - x)^2 + (b - y)^2.

00:26:17.160 --> 00:26:21.430
So here are the two formulas
that are going to allow me to

00:26:21.430 --> 00:26:22.460
set up my problem now.

00:26:22.460 --> 00:26:24.450
So, my goal is to set
it up the way I did

00:26:24.450 --> 00:26:26.940
here, just with formulas.

00:26:26.940 --> 00:26:40.590
And not with diagrams
and not with names.

00:26:40.590 --> 00:26:42.910
So here's what I'd like to do.

00:26:42.910 --> 00:26:46.190
I claim that what's constrained,
if I'm along that

00:26:46.190 --> 00:26:48.910
curve, is that the total
length is constant.

00:26:48.910 --> 00:26:50.730
So that's this statement here.

00:26:50.730 --> 00:26:55.830
The square root of x^2 + y^2
+ this other square root.

00:26:55.830 --> 00:27:02.360
These are the two lengths
of string.

00:27:02.360 --> 00:27:08.210
Is equal to some number,
L, which is constant.

00:27:08.210 --> 00:27:16.040
And this, as I said, is what
I'm calling my constraint.

00:27:16.040 --> 00:27:16.290
Yeah.

00:27:16.290 --> 00:27:20.480
STUDENT: [INAUDIBLE]

00:27:20.480 --> 00:27:24.750
PROFESSOR: So the question is,
shouldn't it be b plus y.

00:27:24.750 --> 00:27:28.210
No, and the reason is that
y is a negative number.

00:27:28.210 --> 00:27:30.300
It's below 0.

00:27:30.300 --> 00:27:39.210
So it's actually the sum, -
y is a positive number.

00:27:39.210 --> 00:27:43.840
Alright, so here's
the formula.

00:27:43.840 --> 00:27:53.000
And then, we want to find the
minimum of something.

00:27:53.000 --> 00:27:56.250
So what is it that we're
finding the minimum of?

00:27:56.250 --> 00:27:58.370
This is actually the hardest
part of the problem,

00:27:58.370 --> 00:27:59.030
conceptually.

00:27:59.030 --> 00:28:01.610
I tried to prepare it,
but it's very hard

00:28:01.610 --> 00:28:02.650
to figure this out.

00:28:02.650 --> 00:28:07.540
We're finding the least what?

00:28:07.540 --> 00:28:10.740
It's y.

00:28:10.740 --> 00:28:11.830
We got a name for that.

00:28:11.830 --> 00:28:17.220
So we want to find
the lowest y.

00:28:17.220 --> 00:28:20.050
Now, the reason why it seems
a little weird is you might

00:28:20.050 --> 00:28:21.770
think of y as just
being a variable.

00:28:21.770 --> 00:28:25.180
But really, y is a function.

00:28:25.180 --> 00:28:32.800
It's really y = y ( x ) is
defined implicitly by the

00:28:32.800 --> 00:28:34.930
constraint equation.

00:28:34.930 --> 00:28:36.420
That's what that curve is.

00:28:36.420 --> 00:28:42.120
And notice the bottom point is
exactly the place where the

00:28:42.120 --> 00:28:46.160
tangent line will
be horizontal.

00:28:46.160 --> 00:28:48.180
Which is just what we want.

00:28:48.180 --> 00:29:03.600
So from the diagram, the bottom
point is where y' = 0.

00:29:03.600 --> 00:29:15.195
So this is the critical point.

00:29:15.195 --> 00:29:25.720
Yeah?

00:29:25.720 --> 00:29:27.540
STUDENT: [INAUDIBLE]

00:29:27.540 --> 00:29:28.440
PROFESSOR: Exactly.

00:29:28.440 --> 00:29:32.440
So I'm deriving for you, so the
question is, could I have

00:29:32.440 --> 00:29:35.590
just tried to find y'
= 0 to begin with.

00:29:35.590 --> 00:29:37.390
The answer is yes, absolutely.

00:29:37.390 --> 00:29:39.070
And in fact I'm leading
in that direction.

00:29:39.070 --> 00:29:42.400
I'm just showing you, so I'm
trying to make the following,

00:29:42.400 --> 00:29:43.930
very subtle, point.

00:29:43.930 --> 00:29:49.500
Which is in maximum-minimum
problems, we always have to

00:29:49.500 --> 00:29:51.130
keep track of two things.

00:29:51.130 --> 00:29:55.110
Often the interesting point
is the critical point.

00:29:55.110 --> 00:29:56.840
And that indeed turns out
to be the case here.

00:29:56.840 --> 00:29:59.840
But we always have to
check the ends.

00:29:59.840 --> 00:30:02.125
And so there are several ways
of checking the ends.

00:30:02.125 --> 00:30:03.490
One is, we did this
physical problem.

00:30:03.490 --> 00:30:05.410
We can see that it's
coming up here.

00:30:05.410 --> 00:30:06.610
We can see that it's
coming up here.

00:30:06.610 --> 00:30:10.480
Therefore the bottom must be
at this critical point.

00:30:10.480 --> 00:30:14.140
So that's OK, so that's one
way of checking it.

00:30:14.140 --> 00:30:17.570
Another way of checking it is
the reasoning that I just

00:30:17.570 --> 00:30:19.330
gave. But it's really
the same reasoning.

00:30:19.330 --> 00:30:21.890
I'm pointing to this thing and
I'm showing you that the

00:30:21.890 --> 00:30:23.010
bottom is somewhere
in the middle.

00:30:23.010 --> 00:30:26.470
So, therefore, it is a place
of horizontal tangency.

00:30:26.470 --> 00:30:28.970
That's the reasoning
that I'm using.

00:30:28.970 --> 00:30:32.570
So, again, this is to avoid
having to evaluate a limit of

00:30:32.570 --> 00:30:35.300
an end or to use the second
derivative test, which is a

00:30:35.300 --> 00:30:42.310
total catastrophe in this case.

00:30:42.310 --> 00:30:45.470
OK, now.

00:30:45.470 --> 00:30:48.780
There's one other thing that you
might know about this if

00:30:48.780 --> 00:30:51.580
you've seen this geometric
construction before.

00:30:51.580 --> 00:30:54.300
With a string and chalk.

00:30:54.300 --> 00:30:58.070
Which is that this curve
is an eclipse.

00:30:58.070 --> 00:30:59.750
It turns out, this is a
piece of an eclipse.

00:30:59.750 --> 00:31:00.870
It's a huge ellipse.

00:31:00.870 --> 00:31:02.280
These two points turn
out to be the

00:31:02.280 --> 00:31:05.500
so-called foci of the ellipse.

00:31:05.500 --> 00:31:09.530
However, that geometric fact is
totally useless for solving

00:31:09.530 --> 00:31:10.860
this problem.

00:31:10.860 --> 00:31:12.390
Completely useless.

00:31:12.390 --> 00:31:14.850
If you actually write out the
formulas for the ellipse,

00:31:14.850 --> 00:31:16.740
you'll discover that you
have a much harder

00:31:16.740 --> 00:31:18.090
problem on your hands.

00:31:18.090 --> 00:31:22.460
And it will take you twice or
ten times as long, so, it's

00:31:22.460 --> 00:31:25.670
true that it's an ellipse,
but it doesn't help.

00:31:25.670 --> 00:31:29.510
OK, so what we're going to do
instead is much simpler.

00:31:29.510 --> 00:31:32.660
We're going to leave this
expression along and we're

00:31:32.660 --> 00:31:35.480
just going to differentiate
implicitly.

00:31:35.480 --> 00:31:42.770
So again, we use implicit
differentiation on the

00:31:42.770 --> 00:31:49.430
constraint equation.

00:31:49.430 --> 00:31:51.350
So that's the equation which
is directly above me

00:31:51.350 --> 00:31:54.310
there, at the top.

00:31:54.310 --> 00:31:57.470
And I have to differentiate
it with respect to x.

00:31:57.470 --> 00:31:59.450
So that's a little ugly,
but we've done

00:31:59.450 --> 00:32:01.080
this a few times before.

00:32:01.080 --> 00:32:03.630
When you differentiate a square
root, the square root

00:32:03.630 --> 00:32:08.230
goes into the denominator.

00:32:08.230 --> 00:32:11.500
And there's a factor of 1/2, so
there's a 2x which cancels.

00:32:11.500 --> 00:32:12.750
So I claim it's this.

00:32:12.750 --> 00:32:17.180
Now, because y depends on x,
there's also a y y' here.

00:32:17.180 --> 00:32:21.930
So technically speaking, it's
twice this with a half.

00:32:21.930 --> 00:32:24.310
2 / 2 times that.

00:32:24.310 --> 00:32:26.240
So that's the differentiation
of the first

00:32:26.240 --> 00:32:30.790
piece of this guy.

00:32:30.790 --> 00:32:33.330
Now I'm going to do this second
one, and it's also the

00:32:33.330 --> 00:32:34.060
chain rule.

00:32:34.060 --> 00:32:39.150
But you're just going to have
to let me do it for you.

00:32:39.150 --> 00:32:43.230
Because it's just a little bit
too long for you to pay

00:32:43.230 --> 00:32:43.880
attention to.

00:32:43.880 --> 00:32:46.580
It turns out there's a minus
sign that comes out, because

00:32:46.580 --> 00:32:49.710
there's a - x and a - y there.

00:32:49.710 --> 00:32:52.880
And then the numerator, the
denominator is the same

00:32:52.880 --> 00:32:55.100
massive square root.

00:32:55.100 --> 00:32:59.920
So it's (a - x)^2 ( b - y)^2.

00:32:59.920 --> 00:33:05.830
And the numerator is a
- x, which is what

00:33:05.830 --> 00:33:07.750
replaces the x over here.

00:33:07.750 --> 00:33:13.660
And then another term,
which is (b - y)y'.

00:33:13.660 --> 00:33:15.960
I claim that that's analogous
to what I did

00:33:15.960 --> 00:33:17.140
in the first term.

00:33:17.140 --> 00:33:20.110
And you'll just have to check
this on your own.

00:33:20.110 --> 00:33:21.630
Because I did it too
fast for you to be

00:33:21.630 --> 00:33:23.730
able to check yourself.

00:33:23.730 --> 00:33:25.300
Now, that's going to
be equal to what on

00:33:25.300 --> 00:33:26.190
the right-hand side.

00:33:26.190 --> 00:33:29.510
What's the derivative of
L with respect to x?

00:33:29.510 --> 00:33:30.540
It's 0.

00:33:30.540 --> 00:33:32.300
It's not changing
in the problem.

00:33:32.300 --> 00:33:37.630
Although my parachute
stuff stretches.

00:33:37.630 --> 00:33:40.700
We tried to stretch it to
its fullest extent.

00:33:40.700 --> 00:33:45.100
So that we kept it fixed,
that was the goal here.

00:33:45.100 --> 00:33:50.380
So now, this looks like
a total mess.

00:33:50.380 --> 00:33:52.940
But, it's not.

00:33:52.940 --> 00:33:54.440
And let me show you why.

00:33:54.440 --> 00:33:57.110
It simplifies a great deal.

00:33:57.110 --> 00:34:01.140
And let me show you
exactly how.

00:34:01.140 --> 00:34:04.220
So, first of all, the whole
point is we're looking for the

00:34:04.220 --> 00:34:06.860
place where y' = 0.

00:34:06.860 --> 00:34:14.080
So that means that these
terms go away. y' = 0.

00:34:14.080 --> 00:34:16.690
So they're gone.

00:34:16.690 --> 00:34:21.070
And now what we have is the
following equation.

00:34:21.070 --> 00:34:27.590
It's x / square root of x^2 +
y^2 squared is equal to, if I

00:34:27.590 --> 00:34:30.630
put it on the other side the
minus sign is changed to a

00:34:30.630 --> 00:34:37.130
plus sign. a - x divided by this
other massive object, (a

00:34:37.130 --> 00:34:43.300
- x)^2 + (b - y)^2.

00:34:43.300 --> 00:34:45.510
So this is what it's
simplifies to.

00:34:45.510 --> 00:34:51.020
Now again, that also might
look complicated to you.

00:34:51.020 --> 00:34:57.320
But I claim that this is
something, this is a kind of

00:34:57.320 --> 00:35:01.980
equilibrium equation that can be
interpreted geometrically,

00:35:01.980 --> 00:35:05.360
in a way that is very meaningful
and important.

00:35:05.360 --> 00:35:09.330
So first of all, let me observe
for you that this x is

00:35:09.330 --> 00:35:10.730
something on our picture.

00:35:10.730 --> 00:35:12.760
And the square root
of x^2 + y^2 is

00:35:12.760 --> 00:35:14.160
something on our picture.

00:35:14.160 --> 00:35:19.230
Namely, if I go over to the
picture, here was x and this

00:35:19.230 --> 00:35:20.760
was a right triangle.

00:35:20.760 --> 00:35:25.700
And this hypotenuse was square
root of x^2 + y^2.

00:35:25.700 --> 00:35:31.680
So, if I call this angle
alpha, then this

00:35:31.680 --> 00:35:34.330
is the sine of alpha.

00:35:34.330 --> 00:35:34.700
Right?

00:35:34.700 --> 00:35:36.950
It's a right triangle, that's
the opposite leg.

00:35:36.950 --> 00:35:44.940
So this guy is the
sine of alpha.

00:35:44.940 --> 00:35:48.850
Similarly, the other side has
an interpretation for the

00:35:48.850 --> 00:35:50.800
other right triangle.

00:35:50.800 --> 00:35:56.245
If this angle is beta, then the
opposite side is a - x,

00:35:56.245 --> 00:36:00.850
and the hypotenuse is what was
in the denominator over there.

00:36:00.850 --> 00:36:10.130
So this side is sine of beta.

00:36:10.130 --> 00:36:14.850
And so what this condition
is telling us is

00:36:14.850 --> 00:36:19.230
that alpha = beta.

00:36:19.230 --> 00:36:22.620
Which is the hidden symmetry
in the problem.

00:36:22.620 --> 00:36:25.600
I don't know if you can actually
see it when I show

00:36:25.600 --> 00:36:28.490
you this thing.

00:36:28.490 --> 00:36:33.120
But, no matter how I tilt it,
actually the two angles from

00:36:33.120 --> 00:36:39.330
the horizontal are the same.

00:36:39.330 --> 00:36:41.230
In the middle it's kind
of obvious that that

00:36:41.230 --> 00:36:42.540
should be the case.

00:36:42.540 --> 00:36:44.510
But on the sides it's
not obvious that

00:36:44.510 --> 00:36:46.820
that's what's happening.

00:36:46.820 --> 00:36:49.955
Now, this has even, so that's
a symmetry, if you like, of

00:36:49.955 --> 00:36:50.590
the situation.

00:36:50.590 --> 00:36:52.590
These two angles are equal.

00:36:52.590 --> 00:36:55.440
But there's something
more to be said.

00:36:55.440 --> 00:36:58.870
If you do a forced diagram for
this, what you'll discover is

00:36:58.870 --> 00:37:03.680
that the tension on the
two lines is the same.

00:37:03.680 --> 00:37:05.980
Which means that when you
build something which is

00:37:05.980 --> 00:37:11.350
hanging like this, it will
involve the least stress.

00:37:11.350 --> 00:37:14.340
If you hang something very
heavy, and one side carries

00:37:14.340 --> 00:37:16.700
twice as much load as the other,
then you have twice as

00:37:16.700 --> 00:37:19.260
much chance of its falling
and breaking.

00:37:19.260 --> 00:37:23.090
If they each hold the same
strength, then you've

00:37:23.090 --> 00:37:26.320
distributed the load in a
much more balanced way.

00:37:26.320 --> 00:37:29.170
So this is a kind of a balance
condition, and it's very

00:37:29.170 --> 00:37:32.950
typical of minimization
problems. And fortunately,

00:37:32.950 --> 00:37:35.810
there are nice solutions which
distribute the weight

00:37:35.810 --> 00:37:37.020
reasonably well.

00:37:37.020 --> 00:37:41.290
That's certainly the principal
of suspension bridges.

00:37:41.290 --> 00:37:42.820
So yeah, one more question.

00:37:42.820 --> 00:37:44.760
STUDENT: [INAUDIBLE]

00:37:44.760 --> 00:37:49.480
PROFESSOR: OK, so the question
