00:37:49.480 --> 00:37:53.030
the formula for x is and what
the formula for y is.

00:37:53.030 --> 00:37:56.240
And other things, like the
equation for the ellipse and

00:37:56.240 --> 00:37:58.310
lots of other stuff like that.

00:37:58.310 --> 00:38:02.030
Those are things that I will
answer for you in a set of

00:38:02.030 --> 00:38:03.700
notes which I will hand out.

00:38:03.700 --> 00:38:06.310
And they're just a mess.

00:38:06.310 --> 00:38:08.930
You see they're, just as in that
other problem that we did

00:38:08.930 --> 00:38:11.940
last time, there's some
illuminating things you can

00:38:11.940 --> 00:38:15.890
say about the problem and then
there's some messy formulas.

00:38:15.890 --> 00:38:19.270
You know, you want to try to
pick out the simple things

00:38:19.270 --> 00:38:19.930
that you can say.

00:38:19.930 --> 00:38:23.420
In fact, that's a property of
math, you want to focus on the

00:38:23.420 --> 00:38:24.500
more comprehensible things.

00:38:24.500 --> 00:38:26.770
On the other hand,
it can be done.

00:38:26.770 --> 00:38:30.290
It just takes a little
bit of computation.

00:38:30.290 --> 00:38:32.080
So I didn't answer the
question of what

00:38:32.080 --> 00:38:33.630
the lowest y was.

00:38:33.630 --> 00:38:39.020
But I'll do that for you.

00:38:39.020 --> 00:38:42.760
Maybe I'll just mention one more
thing about this problem.

00:38:42.760 --> 00:38:44.410
I'm using problems
from a completely

00:38:44.410 --> 00:38:45.890
different point of view.

00:38:45.890 --> 00:38:50.690
If you sort of roll the ellipse
around, you get the

00:38:50.690 --> 00:38:55.580
same phenomenon from
each place here.

00:38:55.580 --> 00:38:58.170
So it doesn't matter
where a and 0 are.

00:38:58.170 --> 00:38:59.490
You'll get the same
phenomenon.

00:38:59.490 --> 00:39:02.040
That is, the tangent line.

00:39:02.040 --> 00:39:06.030
So, this angle and that
angle will be equal.

00:39:06.030 --> 00:39:10.110
So you can also read that as
being the angle over here and

00:39:10.110 --> 00:39:11.350
the angle over here are equal.

00:39:11.350 --> 00:39:14.300
That is, beta, that is
the complementary

00:39:14.300 --> 00:39:17.290
angles are also equal.

00:39:17.290 --> 00:39:21.730
And if you interpret this as a
ray of light, and this as a

00:39:21.730 --> 00:39:24.670
mirror, then this would be
saying that if you start at

00:39:24.670 --> 00:39:28.290
one focus, every ray of light
will bounce and go to the

00:39:28.290 --> 00:39:29.310
other focus.

00:39:29.310 --> 00:39:32.690
So that's a property that
an ellipse has.

00:39:32.690 --> 00:39:36.460
More precisely, a property that
this kind of curve has.

00:39:36.460 --> 00:39:41.900
And in fact, a few years ago
there was this great piece of

00:39:41.900 --> 00:39:45.210
art at something called the
DeCordova Museum, which I

00:39:45.210 --> 00:39:50.570
recommended very highly to you
go sometime to visit in your

00:39:50.570 --> 00:39:52.460
four years here.

00:39:52.460 --> 00:39:59.000
There was a collection of
miniature golf holes.

00:39:59.000 --> 00:40:02.650
So they had a bunch of mini
golf pieces of art.

00:40:02.650 --> 00:40:04.320
And every one was completely
different from the other.

00:40:04.320 --> 00:40:07.910
And one of them was called
