00:40:11.110 --> 00:40:15.390
And the hole was at the other
focus of the ellipse.

00:40:15.390 --> 00:40:19.070
So, no matter how you hit
the golf ball, it always

00:40:19.070 --> 00:40:21.790
goes into the hole.

00:40:21.790 --> 00:40:24.595
No matter where it bounces,
it just, one bounce

00:40:24.595 --> 00:40:26.820
and it's in the hole.

00:40:26.820 --> 00:40:30.550
So that's actually a consequence
of the computation

00:40:30.550 --> 00:40:40.260
that we just did.

00:40:40.260 --> 00:40:42.170
Time to go on.

00:40:42.170 --> 00:41:06.150
We're going to now talk
about something else.

00:41:06.150 --> 00:41:10.990
So our next topic is
Newton's method.

00:41:10.990 --> 00:41:24.020
Which is one of the greatest
applications of calculus.

00:41:24.020 --> 00:41:27.610
And I'm going to describe
it here for you.

00:41:27.610 --> 00:41:36.940
And we'll illustrate it on an
example, which is solving the

00:41:36.940 --> 00:41:39.970
equation x^2 = 5.

00:41:39.970 --> 00:41:42.000
We're going to find the
square root of 5.

00:41:42.000 --> 00:41:45.520
Now, you can actually solve
any equation this way.

00:41:45.520 --> 00:41:47.710
Any equation that you
understand, you can solve this

00:41:47.710 --> 00:41:49.930
way, essentially.

00:41:49.930 --> 00:41:52.120
So even though I'm doing it
for the square root of 5,

00:41:52.120 --> 00:41:54.240
which is something that you
can figure out on your

00:41:54.240 --> 00:41:59.690
calculator, in fact this is
really at the heart of many of

00:41:59.690 --> 00:42:02.210
the ways in which calculators
work.

00:42:02.210 --> 00:42:04.310
So, the first thing is to
make this problem a

00:42:04.310 --> 00:42:06.420
little bit more abstract.

00:42:06.420 --> 00:42:13.830
We're going to set f
( x ) = x^2 - 5.

00:42:13.830 --> 00:42:19.840
And then we're going
to solve f (x) = 0.

00:42:19.840 --> 00:42:22.980
So this is the sort of
standard form for

00:42:22.980 --> 00:42:24.120
solving such a.

00:42:24.120 --> 00:42:27.360
So you take some either
complicated or simple function

00:42:27.360 --> 00:42:30.310
of x, linear functions are
boring, quadratic functions

00:42:30.310 --> 00:42:32.550
are already interesting.

00:42:32.550 --> 00:42:36.720
And cubic functions, as I've
said a few times, you don't

00:42:36.720 --> 00:42:37.980
even have formulas
for solving.

00:42:37.980 --> 00:42:40.295
So this would be the only method
you have for solving

00:42:40.295 --> 00:42:43.750
them numerically.

00:42:43.750 --> 00:42:45.810
So here's how it works.

00:42:45.810 --> 00:42:50.010
So the idea, I'll plot
this function.

00:42:50.010 --> 00:42:55.810
Here's the function, it's
a parabola, y = x^2 - 5.

00:42:55.810 --> 00:42:57.600
It dips below 0, sorry,
it should be

00:42:57.600 --> 00:43:01.090
centered, but anyway.

00:43:01.090 --> 00:43:06.530
And now the idea here is
to start with a guess.

00:43:06.530 --> 00:43:11.380
And square root of 5 is pretty
close to the square root of 4,

00:43:11.380 --> 00:43:12.360
which is 2.

00:43:12.360 --> 00:43:17.030
So my first guess is going
to be 2, here.

00:43:17.030 --> 00:43:30.510
So start with initial guess.

00:43:30.510 --> 00:43:32.320
So that's our first guess.

00:43:32.320 --> 00:43:37.070
And now, what we're going to do
is we're going to pretend

00:43:37.070 --> 00:43:40.080
that the function is linear.

00:43:40.080 --> 00:43:41.300
That's all we're going to do.

00:43:41.300 --> 00:43:45.710
And then if the function were
linear, we're going to try to

00:43:45.710 --> 00:43:47.550
find where the 0 is.

00:43:47.550 --> 00:43:50.470
So if the function is linear,
what we'll use is we'll plot

00:43:50.470 --> 00:43:58.340
the point where 2 is on, that
is, the point (2, f ( 2 )),

00:43:58.340 --> 00:44:06.660
and then we're going to draw
the tangent line here.

00:44:06.660 --> 00:44:15.810
And this is going to be
our new guess. x = x,

00:44:15.810 --> 00:44:22.420
which I'll call x1.

00:44:22.420 --> 00:44:26.830
So the idea here is that this
point may be somewhat far from

00:44:26.830 --> 00:44:31.250
where it crosses, but this point
will be a little closer.

00:44:31.250 --> 00:44:33.830
And now we're going to do this
over and over again.

00:44:33.830 --> 00:44:38.340
And see how fast it gets to the
place we're aiming for.

00:44:38.340 --> 00:44:42.020
So we have to work out what
the formulas are.

00:44:42.020 --> 00:44:53.700
And that's the strategy.

00:44:53.700 --> 00:45:01.730
So now, the first step here is,
we have our guess, we have

00:45:01.730 --> 00:45:06.020
our tangent line.

00:45:06.020 --> 00:45:13.540
Which has the formula
y - y0 = m(x - x0).

00:45:13.540 --> 00:45:16.220
So that's the general form
for a tangent line.

00:45:16.220 --> 00:45:20.140
And now, I have to tell
you what x1 is.

00:45:20.140 --> 00:45:29.970
In terms of this tangent line.
x1 is the x intercept.

00:45:29.970 --> 00:45:33.420
The tangent line, if you look
over here at the diagram, the

00:45:33.420 --> 00:45:36.220
tangent line is the
orange line.

00:45:36.220 --> 00:45:41.340
Where that crosses the axis,
that's where I want to put x1.

00:45:41.340 --> 00:45:43.530
So that's the x intercept.

00:45:43.530 --> 00:45:46.670
Now, how do you find
the x intercept?

00:45:46.670 --> 00:45:49.760
You find it by setting y = 0.

00:45:49.760 --> 00:45:52.270
That horizontal line is y = 0.

00:45:52.270 --> 00:45:59.790
So I set y = 0, and I get
0 - y0 = m (x1 - x0).

00:45:59.790 --> 00:46:02.300
So I changed two things
in this equation.

00:46:02.300 --> 00:46:04.970
I plugged in 0 here, for y.

00:46:04.970 --> 00:46:07.340
And I said that the place where
that happens is going to

00:46:07.340 --> 00:46:13.050
be where x is x1.

00:46:13.050 --> 00:46:15.530
So now let's solve.

00:46:15.530 --> 00:46:19.700
And what we get here is -
y divided by - sorry,

00:46:19.700 --> 00:46:26.390
-y0 / m = x1 - x0.

00:46:26.390 --> 00:46:30.800
And now I can get a
formula for x1.

00:46:30.800 --> 00:46:46.600
So x1 = x0 - (y0 / m).

00:46:46.600 --> 00:46:53.580
I now need to tell you what this
formula means, in terms

00:46:53.580 --> 00:46:56.070
of the function f.

00:46:56.070 --> 00:46:59.230
So first of all, x0 is
x0, whatever x0 is.

00:46:59.230 --> 00:47:06.230
And y0, I claim, is f (x0).

00:47:06.230 --> 00:47:11.080
And m is the slope at
that same place.

00:47:11.080 --> 00:47:17.230
So it's f' (x0).

00:47:17.230 --> 00:47:19.650
And this is the whole story.

00:47:19.650 --> 00:47:25.440
This is the formula which will
enable us to calculate

00:47:25.440 --> 00:47:34.520
basically any root.

00:47:34.520 --> 00:47:36.850
I'm going to repeat this
formula, so I'm going to tell

00:47:36.850 --> 00:47:40.620
you again what Newton's method
is, and put a little more

00:47:40.620 --> 00:47:43.080
colorful box around it.

00:47:43.080 --> 00:47:53.210
So Newton's method involves
the following formula.

00:47:53.210 --> 00:47:58.830
In order to get the n + 1st
point, that's our better and

00:47:58.830 --> 00:48:03.070
better guess, I'm going to take
the nth one and then I'm

00:48:03.070 --> 00:48:04.330
going to plug in this formula.

00:48:04.330 --> 00:48:09.870
So f ( xn ) / f' ( xn ).

00:48:09.870 --> 00:48:14.010
So this is the basic formula,
and if you like, this is the

00:48:14.010 --> 00:48:18.820
idea of just repeating
what I had before.

